      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait i already said the maf sensor seems fine, i've already looked at it. what about vacuum leaks though? could a leak in the intake manifold cause this code? how would i check for that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, vacuum leaks, those sneaky little troublemakers. They can definitely cause a lean condition and throw off that p0171 code. A vacuum leak in the intake manifold can cause the maf sensor to read a lean condition, even if the maf sensor itself is fine.\n\nTo check for a vacuum leak, you'll need to listen for hissing sounds coming from the intake manifold. You can do this by using a mechanic's stethoscope or just your ear. If you hear a hissing sound, there's likely a leak.\n\nAnother way to check for a vacuum leak is to spray carb cleaner around the intake manifold while the engine is running. If the maf sensor reading changes, there's likely a leak. Be careful not to spray any cleaner into the engine, though, as it can cause a mess.\n\nIf you find a vacuum leak, you'll need to repair it. This could involve replacing gaskets, seals, or even the intake manifold itself. Once you've repaired the leak, the p0171 code should go away. Good luck!",
